06127nam a22006855i 9781771990189DE-B159720240307104700.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240307t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a9781771990189  a(DE-B1597)665428  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE76.86.C34bW33 2015eb 7aART0590002bisacsh04a971.23004/9735222300aWe Are Coming Home :bRepatriation and the Restoration of Blackfoot Cultural Confidence /ced. by Gerald T. Conaty. 1aEdmonton, Alberta : bAthabasca University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b14 colour photographs, 16 b&w photographs, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tPrologue -- tBeginnings -- t1 The Development of Museums and their Effects on First Nations -- t2 Niitsitapiisinni: Our Way of Life -- t3 Repatriation Among the Piikani -- t4 Reviving Traditions -- t5 Repatriation Experiences of the Kainai -- t6 Bringing Back Iitskinaiksi at Siksika -- t7 Reviving Our Ways at Siksika -- t8 Moving Toward Repatriation -- t9 The Blackfoot Repatriation: A Personal Epilogue -- t10 Moving Forward -- tAppendix 1 Terms of Reference for the Glenbow Museum’s First Nations Advisory Council -- tAppendix 2 Memorandum of Understanding -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1990, Gerald Conaty was hired as senior curator of ethnology at the Glenbow Museum, with the particular mandate of improving the museum’s relationship with Aboriginal communities. That same year, the Glenbow had taken its first tentative steps toward repatriation by returning sacred objects to First Nations’ peoples. These efforts drew harsh criticism from members of the provincial government. Was it not the museum’s primary legal, ethical, and fiduciary responsibility to ensure the physical preservation of its collections? Would the return of a sacred bundle to ceremonial use not alter and diminish its historical worth and its value to the larger society? Undaunted by such criticism, Conaty oversaw the return of more than fifty medicine bundles to Blackfoot and Cree communities between the years of 1990 and 2000, at which time the First Nations Sacred Ceremonial Objects Repatriation Act (FNSCORA)—still the only repatriation legislation in Canada—was passed. “Repatriation,” he wrote, “is a vital component in the creation of an equitable, diverse, and respectful society.” We Are Coming Home is the story of the highly complex process of repatriation as described by those intimately involved in the work, notably the Piikuni, Siksika, and Kainai elders who provided essential oversight and guidance. We also hear from the Glenbow Museum’s president and CEO at the time and from an archaeologist then employed at the Provincial Museum of Alberta who provides an insider’s view of the drafting of FNSCORA. These accounts are framed by Conaty’s reflections on the impact of museums on First Nations, on the history and culture of the Niitsitapi, or Blackfoot, and on the path forward. With Conaty’s passing in August of 2013, this book is also a tribute to his enduring relationships with the Blackfoot, to his rich and exemplary career, and to his commitment to innovation and mindful museum practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural propertyxMoral and ethical aspectszAlberta. 0aCultural propertyxRepatriationzAlberta. 0aKainah IndiansxMaterial culturezAlberta. 0aMuseum techniqueszAlberta. 0aMuseums and IndianszAlberta. 0aPiegan IndiansxMaterial culturezAlberta. 0aSiksika IndiansxMaterial culturezAlberta. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh  aceremonial bundles, sacred bundles, kainai, siksika, First Nations,